subSubSection.paragraph:
Ventral surface: Prosternum and metasternum finely pubescent. Metepisternum (
Fig. 42
) markedly wider than long, strongly narrowed posteriad. Apex of last visible (VII) abdominal sternite (in male) subtruncate and slightly concave just at tip (
Fig. 43
).

Male genitalia: Median lobe of aedeagus (
Figs 44–46
) in lateral view rather evenly arcuate, C-shaped, with almost straight middle portion of ventral margin and with apical third curved ventrad; in dorsal view almost straight, narrowed to apex in distal third. Terminal lamella moderately short, narrowed to apex. Apical capitulum in lateral view (
Fig. 44
) very oblique, poorly delimited, almost not protruded ventrad and dorsad, narrowly rounded at tip; in caudal view (
Fig. 45
) triangular, somewhat horseshoe-shaped, rather acute, only slightly blunted at tip. Internal sac without distinct spiny patches and other sclerotic elements.
